<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Lily Dizon and Steve Kresal 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 BRIGHT IDEA: The historic train depot in San Juan Capistrano wanted low light 
wattage for its new Metrolink platform for the serenity of nearby Los Rios 
residents. That didn't meet Amtrak's brightness standard, and threatened to 
hold up the Metrolink plan. . . . A few days ago the problem was solved: County 
transportation official John Catoe pointed out that trains first arrived at the 
depot in 1895 -- without a light in sight.The city gets to keep its low glow. 
</P>
<P>
 IN THE WORKS: Three Orange County teams have advanced to the upcoming women's 
community college state basketball tournament: Cypress, Golden West and Orange 
Coast. The finals run Thursday through Saturday in Suisun City near Sacramento. 
Says Cypress freshman forward Sara Works: "I knew from the start our team could 
make it; we have so much talent." Averaging 20 points and nine rebounds a game, 
Works was the Most Valuable Player -- along with Orange Coast's LeAnn Kazmer -- 
of the Orange Empire Conference. 
</P>
<P>
 ENGLISH LESSONS: Four Cal State Fullerton faculty members leave for Vietnam on 
Wednesday, to talk about English. They've been invited by a Hanoi-based 
government group to discuss exchange programs and whether the university's 
televised English as a Second Language classes can be transmitted to Vietnam. . 
. . Says UCI's Harry L. Norman, who will take part in the 12-day trip: "My 
understanding is that in Vietnam, there is a great interest in learning 
English." 
</P>
</TEXT>
