<P>
 BANK PROBLEMS: Ventura County National Bank, already facing bad real estate 
loans, has been given a federal deadline of Sept. 30 to raise its capital 
levels (Valley Business, Page 5). . . . The bank's holding company, Ventura 
County National Bancorp of Oxnard, last week posted a fourth-quarter loss of 
$3.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
 MIND TRIPS: A team of students from Simi Valley's Royal High School beat out 
90 other schools in one category of the Odyssey of the Mind contest . . . The 
winning team designed small vehicles that maneuvered a course and burst 
balloons at the finish line.The first-place team heads to San Bernardino in 
April for the state finals. . . . "Kids don't need to be brilliant to 
participate," adviser Judith Heran said. "Just interested." 
</P>
<P>
 BIG TOP: Some Fillmore merchants are back in business for the first time since 
the Jan. 17 quake (B1). . . . Business owners have set up shop in a makeshift 
tent in Fillmore's Central Park. . . . "It feels like you've moved into a 
really nice mall," said Dale Crockett, whose photography shop has relocated to 
the new space. 
</P>
<P>
 HEALTH BACKLASH: Reformed fatties may be sliding back into their bad habits, 
recent surveys show (E1). . . . Despite warnings from health experts about the 
benefits of exercise, a healthy diet and not smoking, some former health nuts 
are slacking off. . . . "I don't see as many people taking their diet and 
exercise regimens seriously," said Lois Zsarnay, a Ventura registered 
dietitian, who counsels clients to steer clear of quick fixes. 
</P>
<P>
