<HEADLINE>
<P>
ACTOR NICHOLSON CHARGED AFTER ATTACK ON CAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHIP JOHNSON, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Oscar-winning actor Jack Nicholson was charged Monday with misdemeanor 
vandalism and assault for allegedly smashing the windshield of a car with a 
golf club because he thought the other driver cut him off in traffic, the Los 
Angeles city attorney's office announced. 
</P>
<P>
 Robert Scott Blank of Hollywood accused Nicholson of attacking Blank's 
Mercedes-Benz on Feb. 8 in North Hollywood, the city attorney's office said. 
</P>
<P>
 Nicholson stepped out of his car at a red light at the intersection of 
Moorpark Way and Riverside Drive and repeatedly struck the windshield and roof 
of Blank's car with a golf club, according to a statement by the city 
attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
 Blank told investigators that he never got out of his car. 
</P>
<P>
 Witnesses said that after the attack Nicholson and a man who got out of the 
car with him returned to Nicholson's car and drove off, the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
 In a separate lawsuit filed in Los Angeles Superior Court last week, Blank, 
38, said he was hurt by flying glass from the windshield and that the attack 
made him fear for his life. 
</P>
<P>
 The criminal complaint filed against Nicholson, for more than 20 years a major 
box office draw, charges him with one count each of vandalism and assault, said 
Rick Schmidt of the city attorney's Van Nuys office. 
</P>
<P>
 Two independent witnesses identified the weapon used in the incident as a golf 
club, and one identified the 57-year-old actor as the attacker, Schmidt said. 
One witness also remembered the license plate number of the vehicle, and the 
city attorney's office used that information to trace the car to Nicholson, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Nicholson's lawyer, Santa Monica attorney Charles R. English, said he had not 
seen the complaint and could not comment. Blank's lawyer did not return several 
calls to his office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
