<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY REVIEW: GTE BUILDING PURCHASE WOULD BRING 650 JOBS TO OXNARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jack Searles 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thousand Oaks-based GTE California is on the verge of purchasing the 
never-used Chevron USA building in northeast Oxnard and installing a 
customer-service center that would bring 650 jobs to the Oxnard Plain. 
</P>
<P>
 GTE officials are expected to decide within two weeks whether the center will 
be in the 115,000-square-foot Chevron structure or the San Bernardino-Riverside 
area. 
</P>
<P>
 But Oxnard is the clear favorite, GTE officials report. 
</P>
<P>
 "Oxnard's chances look good and, if we choose that city, we'll definitely be 
using that building," said Mike Raydo, GTE's public affairs manager. "We also 
like that location because it's much closer than the competing area to our 
offices in Thousand Oaks. And there's an excellent pool of potential employees 
in Ventura County." 
</P>
<P>
 Mike Marcy, a Chevron spokesman, confirmed that the sale to GTE is imminent. 
"It's a matter of crossing the t's and dotting the i's," he said. "We're very 
excited, especially in view of the jobs and economic benefits this would bring 
to Ventura County." 
</P>
<P>
 GTE is tentatively planning to transfer 250 of its employees to the new 
center, and to hire 400 new workers to staff the unit. The facility would 
consolidate work done at a number of GTE offices throughout Southern 
California. 
</P>
<P>
 It would process new service installations, handle customer inquiries and 
dispatch service trucks from other locations. 
</P>
<P>
 Raydo said a price has already been agreed upon for the Chevron structure, but 
he and Marcy declined to disclose the amount. "All I can say is that it's a lot 
less than Chevron paid to build it," Raydo said. 
</P>
<P>
 The building at Rice Avenue and Gonzales Road was completed in 1990 at a cost 
of $15 million. Chevron had planned to base its Southern California regional 
headquarters there, but later decided to move most of its offices to 
Bakersfield. 
</P>
<P>
 The concrete-and-steel structure, surrounded by spacious lawns, has stood 
vacant since its completion. 
</P>
<P>
 It is located in a 60-acre development that borders the Ventura Freeway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
